Introduction

Data-to-text 2

  1. Linearization of the data-structure
    • unique sequence row
  2. Arbitrary ordering of unordered collections in recurrent networks
    • data-to-text structure encoder RNN(LSTM, GRU)
    • RNN input sequential input ( )

Transformer two-level architecture encoder , Decoder

  1. (record) entity encoding
  2. Entity data-structure encoding
  3. Transformer record/entity record/entity

Data

Notation / General Overview

  • Entity $(e_i)$
    • record $\{r_{(i,1)}, r_{(i,2)}, ..., r_{(i,J_{i})}\}$
    • entity Jeff Teague {(PTS,17), (REB,0) ...} record
  • Record
    • $(r_{i,j})$ $(k_{i,j}, v_{i,j})$ pair
    • (PTS,17),PTS key, 17 value
  • Data Structure ${s}$
    • entities $e_i$ , $s:={e_1, e_2, ... , e_I}$
    • Data Structure (Hawks, Magic, Al Horford, Jeff Teague, ....)
  • Text Description
    • t $y_{1:t}$ . $y_{1:T}$
  • Dataset $D$
    • (Data structure, description) pair collection
  • Objective function
    $ \begin{align} \underset{\theta}{argmax\ \mathcal{L} (\theta)} = \underset{\theta}{argmax} \sum_{(s,y)\in D} log P(\hat{y}=y|s; \theta) \end{align} $
  • Decoder
    • Copy-Mechanism two-layers LSTM .
    • inference Beam-Search

Hierarchical Encoding Model

Encoder Diagram

First Layer

  • 2(key, value) $d$ . ($\mathbf k_{i,j}\in \mathbf{R}^d, \mathbf v_{i,j}\in \mathbf{R}^d$)
  • $r_{i,j}$ = $\text{ReLU}(\mathbf W_r[\mathbf k_{i,j} ; \mathbf v_{i,j}]+ \mathbf B_r)$ where $\mathbf W_r \in \mathbf{R}^{2dxd}$ and $\mathbf b_r \in \mathbf{R}^{d}$
  • $\mathbf W_r$ $\mathbf b_r$

Low-level encoder

Entity record collection encoding . Transformer

  1. record embedding $r_{i,j}$ Entity encoding
  2. $r_{i,j}$ hidden representation ${\mathbf h_{i,j}}$ record embedding
  3. [ENT] record . ?
    • Entity record representation vector$(\mathbf h_i)$

High-level encoder

Entity encoding . Transformer

  1. Entity representation $\mathbf h_i$ encoding
  2. Entity hidden state $\mathbf e_i$ $\mathbf h_i$ $\mathbf h_i$
  3. $\mathbf z$ entity representations($\mathbf e_i$) , decoder initialization

Hierarchical Attention

Traditional Hierarchical Attention

Dynamic Context two step . two step Entity Entity record

  1. decoding step t
  2. $e_i$ $\alpha_{i,t}$ attention score(normalized)
  3. $e_i$ $r_{i,j}$ $\beta_{i,j,t}$ attention score(normalized)

Entity record embedding , Data Structure entity representaion .
Dynamic context .
$ \begin{align} \mathbf c_t = \sum_{i=1}^{I}(\alpha_{i,t}(\sum_{j}\beta_{i,j,t} \mathbf r_{i,j})) \,\, \,\,\text{where}\,\,\, \alpha_{i,t} \,\,{\propto} \,\,exp(\mathbf d_t \mathbf W_\alpha \mathbf e_i) \,\,\,\text{and}\,\,\, \beta_{i,j,t} \,\,{\propto} \,\,exp(\mathbf d_t \mathbf W_\beta \mathbf h_{i,j}) \end{align} $

  • $\mathbf d_t$ decoder step t hidden state
  • $\mathbf W_{\alpha} \in \mathbf R^{dxd}$ $\mathbf W_{\beta} \in \mathbf R^{dxd}$
  • $\sum_{i}\alpha_{i,t} = 1 \text{ for all } i \in \{1,...,I \}$
  • $\sum_{j}\beta_{i,j,t} = 1 $

Key-guided Hierarchical Attention

Entity description record type
, , value score . .

  • full record representation $h_{i,j}$ key embedding .
  • $\hat{\beta}_{i,j,t}\,\, {\propto} \,\,exp(\mathbf d_t \mathbf W_{\alpha 2} \mathbf k_{i,j})$

Evaluation

  1. Bilingual Evaluation Understudy(BLEU)
    • Text Generation
    • ngram
    • BLEU -

  2. Information Extraction-oriented metrics(IE)
    • ()
    • Information Extraction Gold Summary
    • Entity-value pair
    • Information Extraction Input : Isaiah Thomas led the team in scoring, totaling 23 points ...
    • Information Extraction Output : (Isaiah Thomas, 23, PTS)
      1. Content Selection(CS)
        • (record)
        • unique relation precision recall
      2. Relation Generation(RG)
        • unique relation precision absolute number
      3. Content Ordering(CO)
        • (record)
        • sequences of records sequences of records normalized Damerau-Levenshtein Distance

Implementation Details

  • low-level, high-level encoder = two-layers multi-head self-attention with two heads.
  • key's embedding size = 20
  • value's embedding size 300
  • hidden layers of the Transformer encoders = 300
  • dropout rate = 0.5
  • batch size = 64
  • optimizer = Adam
  • learning rate = 0.001 , 10K
  • beam size = 5

Model Structure

NMTModel(Encoder, Decoder)

Encoder, Decoder .

  • Encoder : HierarchicalTrasformerEncoder
  • Decoder : HierarchicalRNNDecoder
  • generator : CopyGenerator

HierarchicalTransformerEncoder

Embedding, Unit Encoder, Chunk Encoder .

  • Unit Encoder Low Level Encoder
  • Chunk Encoder High Level Encoder

1. embeddings

  1. value_embeddings : (479->600) vocab 479 600 .
  2. pos_embeddings : (42->20) pos(key) vocab 42 20 .
  3. concat : value_embedding pos_embedding concat.
  4. linear : 620 600 .
  • Config
    • 600 : word_vec_size
    • 20 : feat_vec_size
    • MLP : linear(620->600)

2. Unit Encoder

low level encoder, high level encoder transformer .

  1. TransformerEncoderLayer * num_layer
    • Self-Attention
      • Attention Mask : Record attention Entity record attention block-eye mask (1x672x672)
      • GLU(Gated Linear Unit) :
    • Residual Connection
    • FeedForward
      • Attention output .
  2. Final Normalization
    • Layer normalization


3. Chunk Encoder

  • Unit Encoder output (Entity Representation, $h_i$) input representation vector
  • Unit Encoder
  • Attention Mask
    • Unit Encoder Entity attention 16x28x28

Copy Mechanism

NLP rare, unknown . copy mechanism Pointing the unknown word Pointer Softmax . time-step target 2 . vocab dictionary context copy . context copy pointing .

The Pointer Softmax

  • point
    1. pointing
    2. copy location pointing
  • Basic Components of the Pointer Softmax
    1. Location softmax
      • source text target copy
      • pointer network
      • output dimension context seqeunce word location
    2. Shortlist softmax
      • softmax output layer
    3. Switching network
      • MLP with sigmoid output function
      • context sequence hidden state input binary variable $z_t$ output
      • $z_t=1$ shortlist softmax $z_t=0$ location softmax

Classification Evaluation Metrics

  • Accuracy()


    • $ \begin{align} Accuracy = \frac{TP+TN}{TP+FP+FN+TN} \end{align} $
  • Precision()
    • Y Y

      $ \begin{align} Precision = \frac{TP}{TP+FP} \end{align} $
  • Recall()
    • Y Y


    • $ \begin{align} Recall = \frac{TP}{TP+FN} \end{align} $
  • F1-Score
    • Precision recall score

      $ \begin{align} \text{F1 Score} = 2*\frac{Precision * Recall}{Precision+Recall} \end{align} $

  • 2
